{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01S3WHZVXzonU5deAzj4ea9w","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I can see the issue. The Owner entity uses `@Column(name = COL_LASTNAME)` where `COL_LASTNAME = \"lastName\"` - so Hibernate creates the column as `lastName` (camelCase). But looking at the error, the column name in the data.sql INSERT is `lastname` (all lowercase). Since Hibernate generates the DDL with `create` mode, let me check what column names Hibernate would actually produce. With `spring.jpa.hibernate.ddl-auto=create`, Hibernate will use the `@Column(name = ...)` annotations. For `Owner`:\n- `COL_LASTNAME = \"lastName\"` - Hibernate will create column `lastName` (PostgreSQL lowercases unquoted identifiers to `lastname`)\n- The INSERT in data.sql also uses `lastname` which should match after PostgreSQL lowercasing.\n\nWait, re-reading the error: `column \"lastname\" of relation \"owner\" does not exist`. The issue might be that the actual column name from Hibernate's physical naming strategy in Spring Boot defaults to `last_name` (it converts camelCase to snake_case by default). Let me check all the entities to understand the column naming. Spring Boot's `SpringPhysicalNamingStrategy` converts `lastName` → `last_name`. But the `@Column(name=...)` value should be used as-is... Actually, Spring Boot's default physical naming strategy also applies to explicit `@Column(name=...)` values, converting `lastName` to `last_name`.\n\nThis is the core issue. I need to fix the data.sql to use the actual column names that Hibernate + Spring's physical naming strategy will produce. The simplest fix is to disable the implicit physical naming strategy so `@Column(name=...)` values are used literally. Or better, I'll just fix the data.sql to match what Spring Boot's naming strategy produces.\n\nLet me first read all entity files to understand the column mappings, then fix data.sql accordingly."}],"stop_reason":