{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_bdrk_01U6oSJ8sMJNDkpudaX4Zjxn","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now with `PhysicalNamingStrategyStandardImpl`, the column names in `@Column(name=...)` will be used as-is. PostgreSQL lowercases unquoted identifiers, so `lastName` → `lastname`, `firstName` → `first_name` (stays as is since it has underscore). Let me verify the data.sql column names match. The data.sql already has `lastname`, `first_name`, `housenumber`, etc. which will match what PostgreSQL creates after lowercasing the annotation values.\n\nBut wait - there's also the issue with fields that have NO explicit `@Column` annotation (like `houseNumber` in Owner). With `ImplicitNamingStrategyLegacyJpaImpl` and `PhysicalNamingStrategyStandardImpl`, the field name `houseNumber` without `@Column` would become `houseNumber` → PostgreSQL lowercases to `housenumber`. But Owner DOES have `@Column(name = COL_HOUSENUMBER)` where `COL_HOUSENUMBER = \"housenumber\"`, so it's fine.\n\nLet me also check if there are any sequence naming issues. Now let me also look at the repository queries since they use field names not column names:"}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":805,"cache_read_input_tokens":66081,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":805,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":448},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8a6bcbcb-6946-47c7-9325-248dd051e737","uuid":"6d3dc317-d087-4545-9ed7-d7050198ea1f"}
